{"title_page": "Horned lark", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{fossilrange|Calabrian|Present}}\n| image = Shore Lark.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22717434/0 |title=''Eremophila alpestris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Eremophila (bird)\n| species = alpestris\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = See text\n| synonyms = *''Alauda alpestris'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n* ''Chionophila alpestris'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758)}}\n* ''Otocorys alpestris'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758)}}\n| range_map = Eremophila alpestris distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = Distribution map of horned lark\n{{leftlegend|yellow|breeding area|outline=gray}}\n{{leftlegend|#047200|all-year area|outline=gray}}\n{{leftlegend|blue|nonbreeding area|outline=gray}}\n}}\n\nThe '''horned lark''' (''Eremophila alpestris''), called the '''shore lark''' in Europe, is a species of [[lark]] in the family [[Alaudidae]] found across the northern hemisphere.\n\n==Taxonomy, evolution and systematics==\nThe specific ''alpestris'' is [[Latin]] and means \"of the high mountains\", from ''Alpes'', the [[Alps]].<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher= Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n42 42], 148}}</ref>\n\nThe horned lark was originally classified in the genus ''[[Alauda]]''.\n\nThe horned lark Is suggested to have diverged from Temnick's lark around the Early-Middle Pleistocene, according to genomic divergence estimates.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Ghorbani|first=Fatemeh|last2=Aliabadian|first2=Mansour|last3=Olsson|first3=Urban|last4=Donald|first4=Paul F.|last5=Khan|first5=Aleem A.|last6=Alstr\u00f6m|first6=Per|date=January 2020|title=Mitochondrial phylogeography of the genus Eremophila confirms underestimated species diversity in the Palearctic|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10336-019-01714-2|journal=Journal of Ornithology|language=en|volume=161|issue=1|pages=297\u2013312|doi=10.1007/s10336-019-01714-2|issn=2193-7192}}</ref> The Horned lark is known from around a dozen localities of [[Late Pleistocene]] age, including those in Italy,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=CARRERA|first=Lisa|last2=PAVIA|first2=Marco|last3=PERESANI|first3=Marco|last4=ROMANDINI|first4=Matteo|date=2018|title=Late Pleistocene fossil birds from Buso Doppio del Broion Cave (North-Eastern Italy): implications for palaeoecology, palaeoenvironment and palaeoclimate|url=http://doi.org/10.4435/BSPI.2018.10|journal=Bollettino della Societ\u00e0 Paleontologica Italiana|issue=2|pages=145\u2013174|doi=10.4435/BSPI.2018.10|issn=0375-7633}}</ref> Russia, The United Kingdom and the United States. The earliest known fossil is from the [[Calabrian (stage)|Calabrian]] of Spain, around 1\u20130.8 million years old.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=S\u00e1nchez-Marco|first=Antonio|date=September 1999|title=Implications of the avian fauna for paleoecology in the Early Pleistocene of the Iberian Peninsula|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0047248499903457|journal=Journal of Human Evolution|language=en|volume=37|issue=3-4|pages=375\u2013388|doi=10.1006/jhev.1999.0345}}</ref> In 2020 a 46,000 year old frozen specimen was described from the Russian Far East.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dussex|first=Nicolas|last2=Stanton|first2=David W. G.|last3=Sigeman|first3=Hanna|last4=Ericson|first4=Per G. P.|last5=Gill|first5=Jacquelyn|last6=Fisher|first6=Daniel C.|last7=Protopopov|first7=Albert V.|last8=Herridge|first8=Victoria L.|last9=Plotnikov|first9=Valery|last10=Hansson|first10=Bengt|last11=Dal\u00e9n|first11=Love|date=2020-02-21|title=Biomolecular analyses reveal the age, sex and species identity of a near-intact Pleistocene bird carcass|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/s42003-020-0806-7|journal=Communications Biology|volume=3|issue=1|doi=10.1038/s42003-020-0806-7|issn=2399-3642}}</ref>\n\nRecent genetic analysis has suggested that the species consists of six [[clades]] that in the future may warrant recognition as separate species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Drovetski|first=Sergei V.|last2=Rakovi\u0107|first2=Marko|last3=Semenov|first3=Georgy|last4=Fadeev|first4=Igor V.|last5=Red'kin|first5=Yaroslav A.|date=2014-01-01|title=Limited phylogeographic signal in sex-linked and autosomal loci despite geographically, ecologically, and phenotypically concordant structure of mtDNA variation in the Holarctic avian genus Eremophila|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=9|issue=1|pages=e87570|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0087570|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3907499|pmid=24498139}}</ref> A 2020 study also suggested splitting of the species, but into 4 species instead, the Himalayan Horned Lark ''E. longirostris,'' Mountain Horned Lark ''E. penicillata,'' Common Horned Lark ''E. alpestris (sensu stricto),'' alongside Temnick's Lark.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Subspecies ===\nForty-two [[subspecies]] are recognized:<ref>{{Cite journal|title=IOC World Bird List 6.4|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/ioc-lists/crossref|journal=IOC World Bird List Datasets|doi=10.14344/ioc.ml.6.4}}</ref> \n* '''Pallid horned lark''' (''E. a. arcticola'') \u2013 <small>([[Harry C. Oberholser|Oberholser]], 1902)</small>: Found from northern Alaska to [[British Columbia]] (western Canada)\n* '''Hoyt's horned lark''' (''E. a. hoyti'') \u2013 <small>([[Louis B. Bishop|Bishop]], 1896)</small>: Found in northern Canada\n* '''Northern American horned lark''' (''E. a. alpestris'') \u2013 <small>([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])</small>: Found in eastern Canada\n* '''Dusky horned lark''' (''E. a. merrilli'') \u2013 <small>([[Jonathan Dwight|Dwight]], 1890)</small>: Found on western coast of Canada and USA\n* '''Streaked horned lark''' (''E. a. strigata'') \u2013 <small>([[Henry Henshaw|Henshaw]], 1884)</small>: Found on coastal southern British Columbia (western Canada) to coastal [[Oregon]] (western USA)\n* '''St. Helens horned lark''' (''E. a. alpina'') \u2013 <small>([[Stanley G. Jewett|Jewett]], 1943)</small>: Found on mountains of western [[Washington (state)|Washington]] (northwestern USA)\n* '''Oregon horned lark''' (''E. a. lamprochroma'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1932)</small>: Found on inland mountains of western USA\n* '''Desert horned lark''' (''E. a. leucolaema'') \u2013 <small>[[Elliott Coues|Coues]], 1874</small>: Also known as the pallid horned lark. Found from southern [[Alberta]] (southwestern Canada) through north-central and central USA\n* '''Saskatchewan horned lark''' (''E. a. enthymia'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found from south-central Canada to [[Oklahoma]] and [[Texas]] (central USA)\n* '''Prairie horned lark''' (''E. a. praticola'') \u2013 <small>(Henshaw, 1884)</small>: Found in southeastern Canada, northeastern and east-central USA\n* '''Sierra horned lark''' (''E. a. sierrae'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1920)</small>: Also known as the '''Sierra Nevada horned lark'''. Found on mountains of northeastern [[California]] (western USA)\n* '''Ruddy horned lark''' (''E. a. rubea'') \u2013 <small>(Henshaw, 1884)</small>: Found in central California (western USA)\n* '''Utah horned lark''' (''E. a. utahensis'') \u2013 <small>([[William H. Behle|Behle]], 1938)</small>: Found on mountains of west-central USA\n* '''Island horned lark''' (''E. a. insularis'') \u2013 <small>(Dwight, 1890)</small>: Found on islands off southern California (western USA)\n* '''California horned lark''' (''E. a. actia'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found on coastal mountains of southern California (western USA) and northern [[Baja California]] (northwestern Mexico)\n* '''Mohave horned lark''' (''E. a. ammophila'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in deserts of southeastern California and southwestern [[Nevada]] (southwestern USA)\n* '''Sonora horned lark''' (''E. a. leucansiptila'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in deserts of southern Nevada, western [[Arizona]] (southwestern USA) and northwestern Mexico\n* '''Montezuma horned lark''' (''E. a. occidentalis'') \u2013 <small>([[George A. McCall|McCall]], 1851)</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found in northern Arizona to central [[New Mexico]] (southwestern USA)\n* '''Scorched horned lark''' (''E. a. adusta'') \u2013 <small>(Dwight, 1890)</small>: Found in southern Arizona and southern New Mexico (southwestern USA), possibly north-central Mexico\n* '''Magdalena horned lark''' (''E. a. enertera'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1907)</small>: Found in central Baja California (northwestern Mexico)\n* '''Texas horned lark''' (''E. a. giraudi'') \u2013 <small>(Henshaw, 1884)</small>: Found in coastal south-central USA and northeastern Mexico\n* ''E. a. aphrasta'' \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] and [[Durango]] (northwestern Mexico)\n* ''E. a. lactea'' \u2013 <small>[[Allan Robert Phillips|Phillips, AR]], 1970</small>: Found in [[Coahuila]] (north-central Mexico)\n* ''E. a. diaphora'' \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in southern Coahuila to northeastern [[Puebla]] (north-central and eastern Mexico)\n* '''Mexican horned lark''' (''E. a. chrysolaema'') \u2013 <small>([[Johann Georg Wagler|Wagler]], 1831)</small>: Originally described as a separate species in the genus ''[[Alauda]]''. Found from west-central to east-central Mexico\n* ''E. a. oaxacae'' \u2013 <small>([[Edward William Nelson|Nelson]], 1897)</small>: Found in southern Mexico\n* '''Colombian horned lark''' (''E. a. peregrina'') \u2013 <small>([[Philip Sclater|Sclater, PL]], 1855)</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found in Colombia\n* '''Shore lark''' (''E. a. flava'') \u2013 <small>([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin, JF]], 1789)</small>: Originally described as a separate species in the genus ''Alauda''. Found in northern Europe and northern Asia\n* '''Steppe horned lark''' (''E. a. brandti'') \u2013 <small>([[Henry Eeles Dresser|Dresser]], 1874)</small>: Also known as '''Brandt's horned lark'''. Originally described as a separate species. Found from southeastern European Russia to western Mongolia and northern China\n* '''Moroccan horned lark''' (''E. a. atlas'') \u2013 <small>([[Joseph Whitaker (ornithologist)|Whitaker]], 1898)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in Morocco\n* '''Balkan horned lark''' (''E. a. balcanica'') \u2013 <small>([[Anton Reichenow|Reichenow]], 1895)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in southern [[Balkans]] and Greece\n* ''E. a. kumerloevei'' \u2013 <small>[[Cornelis S. Roselaar|Roselaar]], 1995</small>: Found in western and central [[Asia Minor]]\n* '''Southern horned lark''' (''E. a. penicillata'') \u2013 <small>([[John Gould|Gould]], 1838)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species in the genus ''Alauda''. Found from eastern Turkey and the [[Caucasus]] to Iran\n* '''Lebanon horned lark''' (''E. a. bicornis'') \u2013 <small>([[Christian Ludwig Brehm|Brehm, CL]], 1842)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found from Lebanon to Israel/Syria border\n* '''Pamir horned lark''' (''E. a. albigula'') \u2013 <small>([[Charles Lucien Bonaparte|Bonaparte]], 1850)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found from northeastern Iran and Turkmenistan to northwestern Pakistan\n* ''E. a. argalea'' \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in extreme western China\n* '''Przewalski's lark''' (''E. a. teleschowi'') \u2013 <small>([[Nikolay Przhevalsky|Przewalski]], 1887)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in western and west-central China\n* ''E. a. przewalskii'' \u2013 <small>([[Valentin Bianchi|Bianchi]], 1904)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in northern [[Qinghai]] (west-central China)\n* ''E. a. nigrifrons'' \u2013 <small>(Przewalski, 1876)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in northeastern Qinghai (west-central China)\n* '''Long-billed horned lark''' (''E. a. longirostris'') \u2013 <small>([[Frederic Moore|Moore, F]], 1856)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in northeastern Pakistan and western [[Himalayas]]\n* ''E. a. elwesi'' \u2013 <small>([[William Thomas Blanford|Blanford]], 1872)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found on southern and eastern [[Tibetan Plateau]]\n* ''E. a. khamensis'' \u2013 <small>(Bianchi, 1904)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in southwestern and south-central China\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Horned Lark RWD.jpg|thumb|left|A male at the [[North Carolina Zoo]] in [[Asheboro, North Carolina]], US]]\nUnlike most other [[lark]]s, this is a distinctive-looking species on the ground, mainly brown-grey above and pale below, with a striking black and yellow face pattern. Except for the central feathers, the tail is mostly black, contrasting with the paler body; this contrast is especially noticeable when the bird is in flight. The summer male has black \"horns\", which give this species its American name. North America has a number of races distinguished by the face pattern and back colour of males, especially in summer. The southern European mountain race ''E. a. penicillata'' is greyer above, and the yellow of the face pattern is replaced with white.\n\n[[File:Eremophila alpestris -British Columbia, Canada-8.jpg|thumb|right|In [[British Columbia]], Canada]]\nVocalizations are high-pitched, lisping or tinkling, and weak. The song, given in flight as is common among larks, consists of a few chips followed by a warbling, ascending trill.\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n\n[[File:Horned_lark.jpg|thumb|left|A lark displaying its horns at the [[Rocky Mountain Arsenal National Wildlife Refuge]]]]\n\nThe horned lark breeds across much of North America from the high Arctic south to the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec]], northernmost Europe and Asia and in the mountains of southeast Europe. There is also an isolated population on a plateau in Colombia. It is mainly resident in the south of its range, but northern populations of this [[passerine]] [[bird]] are [[bird migration|migratory]], moving further south in winter.\n\nThis is a bird of open ground. In Eurasia it breeds above the tree line in mountains and the far north. In most of Europe, it is most often seen on seashore flats in winter, leading to the European name. In the UK it is found as a winter stopover along the coasts and in eastern England. In North America, where there are no other larks to compete with, it is also found on farmland, on prairies, in deserts, on golf courses and airports.\n\n== Breeding and Nesting ==\n[[File:Horned Lark, Eremophila alpestris, nestlings begging, baby birds, gape colors, in nest Alberta Canada (3).jpg|thumb|A nest with three chicks in the oil fields of [[Alberta]], Canada]]\n\tMales defend territories from other males during breeding season and females will occasionally chase away intruding females. Courting is composed of the male singing to the female while flying above her in circles. He then will fold his wings in and dive towards the female, opening his wings and landing just before hitting the ground.<ref>\"Horned Lark - Eremophila alpestris | Wildlife Journal Junior\". nhpbs.org.</ref>\nThe nest site is selected in the early spring by only the female and is either a natural depression in the bare ground or she digs a cavity using her bill and feet.<ref name=\"allaboutbirds.org\">\"Horned Lark Life History, All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology\". www.allaboutbirds.org.</ref> She will spend 2\u20134 days preparing the site before building her nest. She weaves fines grasses, cornstalks, small roots, and other plant material and lines it with down, fur, feathers, and occasionally lint. The nest totals to be about 3-4 inches in diameter with the interior diameter about 2.5 inches wide and 1.5 inches deep. It has been notes she often adds a \u201cdoorstep\u201d of pebbles, corncobs, or dung on one side of the nest. The speculation is, it is used to cover the excavated dirt and hid her nest more.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">\"Horned Lark\". American Bird Conservancy.</ref>\n\tShe will lay a clutch of 2-5 gray [[bird egg|eggs]] with brown spots, each about 1 inch long and half an inch wide. Incubation will take 10\u201312 days until hatching and then the nestling period will take 8\u201310 days. During the nestling period, the chick is fed and defended by both parents. The A female in the south can lay 2-3 broods a year while in the north, 1 brood a year is more common.<ref>\"Horned Lark\". Audubon. 13 November 2014.</ref>\n The structure of Horned Lark nests can vary depending on the microclimate, prevailing weather and predation risk, revealing flexibility in nesting behaviour to adjust to changing environmental conditions to maintain nest survival and nestling size development.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= de Zwaan, D.R. |author2= Martin, K. |  year=2018| title= Substrate and structure of ground nests have fitness consequences for an alpine songbird| journal=Ibis| volume=160| pages= 790\u2013804| doi=10.1111/ibi.12582 | issue=4}}</ref>\n\n== Status and conservation ==\nHorned Lark populations are declining according to the North American Breeding Bird Survey. In 2016, the Partners in Flight Landbird Conservation Plan detailed the Horned Lark as a \u201cCommon Bird in Steep Decline,\u201d but the Horned Lark as of 2016 is not on the State of North America\u2019s Birds\u2019 Watch List.<ref name=\"allaboutbirds.org\"/> This species\u2019 decline could be contributed to the loss of habitat due to agricultural pesticides, the disturbed sites the birds prefer reverting back to forested lands through reforestation efforts, urbanization and human encroachment as well as collisions with wind turbines.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> In the open areas of western North America, horned larks are among the bird species most often killed by wind turbines.<ref>Erickson, W.P., G. D. Johnson, D. P. Young, Jr., M. D. Strickland, R.E. Good, M.Bourassa, K. Bay. 2002. Synthesis and Comparison of Baseline Avian and Bat Use, Raptor Nesting and Mortality Information from Proposed and Existing Wind Developments. Technical Report prepared for Bonneville Power Administration, Portland, Oregon. http://www.bpa.gov/Power/pgc/wind/Avian_and_Bat_Study_12-2002.pdf</ref> In 2013, the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service]] listed the subspecies streaked horned lark as [[threatened species#United States definition|threatened]] under the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=USFWS>{{cite web |title=Species Fact Sheet: Streaked horned lark |url=http://www.fws.gov/oregonfwo/Species/Data/StreakedHornedLark/ |accessdate=2014-08-19 |date=2014-08-05 |publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Beason |first1=Robert |title=Horned Lark (Eremophila alpestris), version 2.0. In The Birds of North America |date=1995 |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |location=Ithaca, New York, USA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark |url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/horned-lark |website=Audubon |language=en |date=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark - Eremophila alpestris {{!}} Wildlife Journal Junior |url=https://nhpbs.org/wild/hornedlark.asp |website=nhpbs.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark |url=https://abcbirds.org/bird/horned-lark |website=American Bird Conservancy |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark Life History, All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology |url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Horned_Lark/lifehistory |website=www.allaboutbirds.org |language=en}}</ref><!-- Condor105:154,109:441. FieldMusNatHistZoolSer18:343. WilsonBull18:47 (compare to current Ohio checklist http://www.ohiobirds.org/publications/OBRClist.pdf). -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* van den Berg, Arnoud (2005) Morphology of Atlas Horned Lark ''[[Dutch Birding]]'' 27(4):256\u20138\n* Small, Brian (2002) The Horned Lark on the Isles of Scilly ''[[Birding World]]'' 15(3): 111\u201320 (discusses a possible Nearctic race bird on the Isles of Scilly in 2001)\n* {{cite journal|author= Dickinson, E.C.|author2= R.W.R.J. Dekker|author3= S. Eck|author4= S. Somadikarta|last-author-amp= yes| title= Systematic notes on Asian birds. 12. Types of the Alaudidae| journal= Zool. Verh. Leiden |volume= 335| year=2001| pages= 85\u2013126 |url= }}\n* {{cite journal| url=https://archive.org/stream/ornithologicalpa02seebrich#page/184/mode/1up| title = On the East-Asiatic Shore-Lark (Otocorys longirostris)|author=Seebohm, H| journal= Ibis | volume=26| issue=2 |pages= 184\u2013188| year=1884| doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.1884.tb01153.x}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Eremophila alpestris|the horned lark}}\n{{Wikispecies|Eremophila alpestris}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050404122221/http://cyberbirding.uib.no/photo/e_alpestris_03.php Picture] \u2013 Cyberbirding\n* [http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Horned_Lark.html Species account] \u2013 Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|horned-lark-eremophila-alpestris|Horned lark}}\n* [http://www.mbr-pwrc.usgs.gov/id/framlst/i4740id.html Horned lark \u2013 ''Eremophila alpestris''] \u2013 USGS Patuxent Bird Identification InfoCenter\n* {{VIREO|horned+lark|Horned lark}}\n* {{IUCN_Map|22717434|Eremophila alpestris}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q207249}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:lark, horned}}\n[[Category:Eremophila (bird)|horned lark]]\n[[Category:Holarctic birds]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|horned lark]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus|horned lark]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{fossilrange|Calabrian|Present}}\n| image = Shore Lark.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22717434/0 |title=''Eremophila alpestris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Eremophila (bird)\n| species = alpestris\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = See text\n| synonyms = *''Alauda alpestris'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n* ''Chionophila alpestris'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758)}}\n* ''Otocorys alpestris'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758)}}\n| range_map = Eremophila alpestris distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = Distribution map of horned lark\n{{leftlegend|yellow|breeding area|outline=gray}}\n{{leftlegend|#047200|all-year area|outline=gray}}\n{{leftlegend|blue|nonbreeding area|outline=gray}}\n}}\n\nThe '''horned lark''' (''Eremophila alpestris''), called the '''shore lark''' in Europe, is a species of [[lark]] in the [[Alaudidae]] family found across the northern hemisphere.\n\n==Taxonomy, evolution and systematics==\nThe specific ''alpestris'' is [[Latin]] and means \"of the high mountains\", from ''Alpes'', the [[Alps]].<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher= Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n42 42], 148}}</ref>\n\nThe horned lark was originally classified in the genus ''[[Alauda]]''.\n\nThe horned lark Is suggested to have diverged from Temnick's lark around the Early-Middle Pleistocene, according to genomic divergence estimates.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Ghorbani|first=Fatemeh|last2=Aliabadian|first2=Mansour|last3=Olsson|first3=Urban|last4=Donald|first4=Paul F.|last5=Khan|first5=Aleem A.|last6=Alstr\u00f6m|first6=Per|date=January 2020|title=Mitochondrial phylogeography of the genus Eremophila confirms underestimated species diversity in the Palearctic|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10336-019-01714-2|journal=Journal of Ornithology|language=en|volume=161|issue=1|pages=297\u2013312|doi=10.1007/s10336-019-01714-2|issn=2193-7192}}</ref> The Horned lark is known from around a dozen localities of [[Late Pleistocene]] age, including those in Italy,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=CARRERA|first=Lisa|last2=PAVIA|first2=Marco|last3=PERESANI|first3=Marco|last4=ROMANDINI|first4=Matteo|date=2018|title=Late Pleistocene fossil birds from Buso Doppio del Broion Cave (North-Eastern Italy): implications for palaeoecology, palaeoenvironment and palaeoclimate|url=http://doi.org/10.4435/BSPI.2018.10|journal=Bollettino della Societ\u00e0 Paleontologica Italiana|issue=2|pages=145\u2013174|doi=10.4435/BSPI.2018.10|issn=0375-7633}}</ref> Russia, The United Kingdom and the United States. The earliest known fossil is from the [[Calabrian (stage)|Calabrian]] of Spain, around 1\u20130.8 million years old.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=S\u00e1nchez-Marco|first=Antonio|date=September 1999|title=Implications of the avian fauna for paleoecology in the Early Pleistocene of the Iberian Peninsula|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0047248499903457|journal=Journal of Human Evolution|language=en|volume=37|issue=3-4|pages=375\u2013388|doi=10.1006/jhev.1999.0345}}</ref> In 2020 a 46,000 year old frozen specimen was described from the Russian Far East.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dussex|first=Nicolas|last2=Stanton|first2=David W. G.|last3=Sigeman|first3=Hanna|last4=Ericson|first4=Per G. P.|last5=Gill|first5=Jacquelyn|last6=Fisher|first6=Daniel C.|last7=Protopopov|first7=Albert V.|last8=Herridge|first8=Victoria L.|last9=Plotnikov|first9=Valery|last10=Hansson|first10=Bengt|last11=Dal\u00e9n|first11=Love|date=2020-02-21|title=Biomolecular analyses reveal the age, sex and species identity of a near-intact Pleistocene bird carcass|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/s42003-020-0806-7|journal=Communications Biology|volume=3|issue=1|doi=10.1038/s42003-020-0806-7|issn=2399-3642}}</ref>\n\nRecent genetic analysis has suggested that the species consists of six [[clades]] that in the future may warrant recognition as separate species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Drovetski|first=Sergei V.|last2=Rakovi\u0107|first2=Marko|last3=Semenov|first3=Georgy|last4=Fadeev|first4=Igor V.|last5=Red'kin|first5=Yaroslav A.|date=2014-01-01|title=Limited phylogeographic signal in sex-linked and autosomal loci despite geographically, ecologically, and phenotypically concordant structure of mtDNA variation in the Holarctic avian genus Eremophila|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=9|issue=1|pages=e87570|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0087570|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3907499|pmid=24498139}}</ref> A 2020 study also suggested splitting of the species, but into 4 species instead, the Himalayan Horned Lark ''E. longirostris,'' Mountain Horned Lark ''E. penicillata,'' Common Horned Lark ''E. alpestris (sensu stricto),'' alongside Temnick's Lark.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Subspecies ===\nForty-two [[subspecies]] are recognized:<ref>{{Cite journal|title=IOC World Bird List 6.4|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/ioc-lists/crossref|journal=IOC World Bird List Datasets|doi=10.14344/ioc.ml.6.4}}</ref> \n* '''Pallid horned lark''' (''E. a. arcticola'') \u2013 <small>([[Harry C. Oberholser|Oberholser]], 1902)</small>: Found from northern Alaska to [[British Columbia]] (western Canada)\n* '''Hoyt's horned lark''' (''E. a. hoyti'') \u2013 <small>([[Louis B. Bishop|Bishop]], 1896)</small>: Found in northern Canada\n* '''Northern American horned lark''' (''E. a. alpestris'') \u2013 <small>([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])</small>: Found in eastern Canada\n* '''Dusky horned lark''' (''E. a. merrilli'') \u2013 <small>([[Jonathan Dwight|Dwight]], 1890)</small>: Found on western coast of Canada and USA\n* '''Streaked horned lark''' (''E. a. strigata'') \u2013 <small>([[Henry Henshaw|Henshaw]], 1884)</small>: Found on coastal southern British Columbia (western Canada) to coastal [[Oregon]] (western USA)\n* '''St. Helens horned lark''' (''E. a. alpina'') \u2013 <small>([[Stanley G. Jewett|Jewett]], 1943)</small>: Found on mountains of western [[Washington (state)|Washington]] (north-western USA)\n* '''Oregon horned lark''' (''E. a. lamprochroma'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1932)</small>: Found on inland mountains of western USA\n* '''Desert horned lark''' (''E. a. leucolaema'') \u2013 <small>[[Elliott Coues|Coues]], 1874</small>: Also known as the pallid horned lark. Found from southern [[Alberta]] (south-western Canada) through north-central and central USA\n* '''Saskatchewan horned lark''' (''E. a. enthymia'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found from south-central Canada to [[Oklahoma]] and [[Texas]] (central USA)\n* '''Prairie horned lark''' (''E. a. praticola'') \u2013 <small>(Henshaw, 1884)</small>: Found in south-eastern Canada, north-eastern and east-central USA\n* '''Sierra horned lark''' (''E. a. sierrae'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1920)</small>: Also known as the '''Sierra Nevada horned lark'''. Found on mountains of north-eastern [[California]] (western USA)\n* '''Ruddy horned lark''' (''E. a. rubea'') \u2013 <small>(Henshaw, 1884)</small>: Found in central California (western USA)\n* '''Utah horned lark''' (''E. a. utahensis'') \u2013 <small>([[William H. Behle|Behle]], 1938)</small>: Found on mountains of west-central USA\n* '''Island horned lark''' (''E. a. insularis'') \u2013 <small>(Dwight, 1890)</small>: Found on islands off southern California (western USA)\n* '''California horned lark''' (''E. a. actia'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found on coastal mountains of southern California (western USA) and northern [[Baja California]] (north-western Mexico)\n* '''Mohave horned lark''' (''E. a. ammophila'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in deserts of south-eastern California and south-western [[Nevada]] (south-western USA)\n* '''Sonora horned lark''' (''E. a. leucansiptila'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in deserts of southern Nevada, western [[Arizona]] (south-western USA) and north-western Mexico\n* '''Montezuma horned lark''' (''E. a. occidentalis'') \u2013 <small>([[George A. McCall|McCall]], 1851)</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found in northern Arizona to central [[New Mexico]] (south-western USA)\n* '''Scorched horned lark''' (''E. a. adusta'') \u2013 <small>(Dwight, 1890)</small>: Found in southern Arizona and southern New Mexico (south-western USA), possibly north-central Mexico\n* '''Magdalena horned lark''' (''E. a. enertera'') \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1907)</small>: Found in central Baja California (north-western Mexico)\n* '''Texas horned lark''' (''E. a. giraudi'') \u2013 <small>(Henshaw, 1884)</small>: Found in coastal south-central USA and north-eastern Mexico\n* ''E. a. aphrasta'' \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] and [[Durango]] (north-western Mexico)\n* ''E. a. lactea'' \u2013 <small>[[Allan Robert Phillips|Phillips, AR]], 1970</small>: Found in [[Coahuila]] (north-central Mexico)\n* ''E. a. diaphora'' \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: Found in southern Coahuila to north-eastern [[Puebla]] (north-central and eastern Mexico)\n* '''Mexican horned lark''' (''E. a. chrysolaema'') \u2013 <small>([[Johann Georg Wagler|Wagler]], 1831)</small>: Originally described as a separate species in the genus ''[[Alauda]]''. Found from west-central to east-central Mexico\n* ''E. a. oaxacae'' \u2013 <small>([[Edward William Nelson|Nelson]], 1897)</small>: Found in southern Mexico\n* '''Colombian horned lark''' (''E. a. peregrina'') \u2013 <small>([[Philip Sclater|Sclater, PL]], 1855)</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found in Colombia\n* '''Shore lark''' (''E. a. flava'') \u2013 <small>([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin, JF]], 1789)</small>: Originally described as a separate species in the genus ''Alauda''. Found in northern Europe and northern Asia\n* '''Steppe horned lark''' (''E. a. brandti'') \u2013 <small>([[Henry Eeles Dresser|Dresser]], 1874)</small>: Also known as '''Brandt's horned lark'''. Originally described as a separate species. Found from south-eastern European Russia to western Mongolia and northern China\n* '''Moroccan horned lark''' (''E. a. atlas'') \u2013 <small>([[Joseph Whitaker (ornithologist)|Whitaker]], 1898)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in Morocco\n* '''Balkan horned lark''' (''E. a. balcanica'') \u2013 <small>([[Anton Reichenow|Reichenow]], 1895)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in southern [[Balkans]] and Greece\n* ''E. a. kumerloevei'' \u2013 <small>[[Cornelis S. Roselaar|Roselaar]], 1995</small>: Found in western and central [[Asia Minor]]\n* '''Southern horned lark''' (''E. a. penicillata'') \u2013 <small>([[John Gould|Gould]], 1838)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species in the genus ''Alauda''. Found from eastern Turkey and the [[Caucasus]] to Iran\n* '''Lebanon horned lark''' (''E. a. bicornis'') \u2013 <small>([[Christian Ludwig Brehm|Brehm, CL]], 1842)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found from Lebanon to Israel/Syria border\n* '''Pamir horned lark''' (''E. a. albigula'') \u2013 <small>([[Charles Lucien Bonaparte|Bonaparte]], 1850)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found from north-eastern Iran and Turkmenistan to north-western Pakistan\n* ''E. a. argalea'' \u2013 <small>(Oberholser, 1902)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in extreme western China\n* '''Przewalski's lark''' (''E. a. teleschowi'') \u2013 <small>([[Nikolay Przhevalsky|Przewalski]], 1887)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in western and west-central China\n* ''E. a. przewalskii'' \u2013 <small>([[Valentin Bianchi|Bianchi]], 1904)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in northern [[Qinghai]] (west-central China)\n* ''E. a. nigrifrons'' \u2013 <small>(Przewalski, 1876)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in north-eastern Qinghai (west-central China)\n* '''Long-billed horned lark''' (''E. a. longirostris'') \u2013 <small>([[Frederic Moore|Moore, F]], 1856)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found in north-eastern Pakistan and western [[Himalayas]]\n* ''E. a. elwesi'' \u2013 <small>([[William Thomas Blanford|Blanford]], 1872)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Originally described as a separate species. Found on southern and eastern [[Tibetan Plateau]]\n* ''E. a. khamensis'' \u2013 <small>(Bianchi, 1904)</small>: This subspecies is also called \"shore lark\". Found in south-western and south-central China\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Horned Lark RWD.jpg|thumb|left|A male at the [[North Carolina Zoo]] in [[Asheboro, North Carolina]], US]]\nUnlike most other [[lark]]s, this is a distinctive-looking species on the ground, mainly brown-grey above and pale below, with a striking black and yellow face pattern. Except for the central feathers, the tail is mostly black, contrasting with the paler body; this contrast is especially noticeable when the bird is in flight. The summer male has black \"horns\", which give this species its American name. North America has a number of races distinguished by the face pattern and back colour of males, especially in summer. The southern European mountain race ''E. a. penicillata'' is greyer above, and the yellow of the face pattern is replaced with white.\n\n[[File:Eremophila alpestris -British Columbia, Canada-8.jpg|thumb|right|In [[British Columbia]], Canada]]\nVocalizations are high-pitched, lisping or tinkling, and weak. The song, given in flight as is common among larks, consists of a few chips followed by a warbling, ascending trill.\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n\n[[File:Horned_lark.jpg|thumb|left|A lark displaying its horns at the [[Rocky Mountain Arsenal National Wildlife Refuge]]]]\n\nThe horned lark breeds across much of North America from the high Arctic south to the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec]], northernmost Europe and Asia and in the mountains of south-east Europe. There is also an isolated population on a plateau in Colombia. It is mainly resident in the south of its range, but northern populations of this [[passerine]] [[bird]] are [[bird migration|migratory]], moving further south in winter.\n\nThis is a bird of open ground. In Eurasia it breeds above the tree line in mountains and the far north. In most of Europe, it is most often seen on seashore flats in winter, leading to the European name. In the UK it can be found as a winter stopover along the coasts and in eastern England. In North America, where there are no other larks to compete with, it is also found on farmland, on prairies, in deserts, on golf courses and airports.\n\n== Breeding and Nesting ==\n[[File:Horned Lark, Eremophila alpestris, nestlings begging, baby birds, gape colors, in nest Alberta Canada (3).jpg|thumb|A nest with three chicks in the oil fields of [[Alberta]], Canada]]\n\tMales defend territories from other males during breeding season and females will occasionally chase away intruding females. Courting is composed of the male singing to the female while flying above her in circles. He then will fold his wings in and dive towards the female, opening his wings and landing just before hitting the ground<ref>\"Horned Lark - Eremophila alpestris | Wildlife Journal Junior\". nhpbs.org.</ref>.\nThe nest site is selected in the early spring by only the female and is either a natural depression in the bare ground or she digs a cavity using her bill and feet<ref>\"Horned Lark Life History, All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology\". www.allaboutbirds.org.</ref>. She will spend 2-4 days preparing the site before building her nest. She weaves fines grasses, cornstalks, small roots, and other plant material and lines it with down, fur, feathers, and occasionally lint. The nest totals to be about 3-4 inches in diameter with the interior diameter about 2.5 inches wide and 1.5 inches deep. It has been notes she often adds a \u201cdoorstep\u201d of pebbles, corncobs, or dung on one side of the nest. The speculation is, it is used to cover the excavated dirt and hid her nest more<ref>\"Horned Lark\". American Bird Conservancy.</ref>.\n\tShe will lay a clutch of 2-5 gray [[bird egg|eggs]] with brown spots, each about 1 inch long and half an inch wide. Incubation will take 10-12 days until hatching and then the nestling period will take 8-10 days. During the nestling period, the chick is fed and defended by both parents. The A female in the south can lay 2-3 broods a year while in the north, 1 brood a year is more common<ref>\"Horned Lark\". Audubon. 13 November 2014.</ref>.\n The structure of Horned Lark nests can vary depending on the microclimate, prevailing weather and predation risk, revealing flexibility in nesting behaviour to adjust to changing environmental conditions to maintain nest survival and nestling size development.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= de Zwaan, D.R. |author2= Martin, K. |  year=2018| title= Substrate and structure of ground nests have fitness consequences for an alpine songbird| journal=Ibis| volume=160| pages= 790\u2013804| doi=10.1111/ibi.12582 | issue=4}}</ref>\n\n== Status and conservation ==\nHorned Lark populations are declining according to the North American Breeding Bird Survey. In 2016, the Partners in Flight Landbird Conservation Plan detailed the Horned Lark as a \u201cCommon Bird in Steep Decline,\u201d but the Horned Lark as of 2016 is not on the State of North America\u2019s Birds\u2019 Watch List<ref>\"Horned Lark Life History, All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology\". www.allaboutbirds.org.</ref>. This species\u2019 decline could be contributed to the loss of habitat due to agricultural pesticides, the disturbed sites the birds prefer reverting back to forested lands through reforestation efforts, urbanization and human encroachment as well as collisions with wind turbines<ref>\"Horned Lark\". American Bird Conservancy.</ref>. In the open areas of western North America, horned larks are among the bird species most often killed by wind turbines.<ref>Erickson, W.P., G. D. Johnson, D. P. Young, Jr., M. D. Strickland, R.E. Good, M.Bourassa, K. Bay. 2002. Synthesis and Comparison of Baseline Avian and Bat Use, Raptor Nesting and Mortality Information from Proposed and Existing Wind Developments. Technical Report prepared for Bonneville Power Administration, Portland, Oregon. http://www.bpa.gov/Power/pgc/wind/Avian_and_Bat_Study_12-2002.pdf</ref> In 2013, the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service]] listed the subspecies streaked horned lark as [[threatened species#United States definition|threatened]] under the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=USFWS>{{cite web |title=Species Fact Sheet: Streaked horned lark |url=http://www.fws.gov/oregonfwo/Species/Data/StreakedHornedLark/ |accessdate=2014-08-19 |date=2014-08-05 |publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Beason |first1=Robert |title=Horned Lark (Eremophila alpestris), version 2.0. In The Birds of North America |date=1995 |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |location=Ithaca, New York, USA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark |url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/horned-lark |website=Audubon |language=en |date=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark - Eremophila alpestris {{!}} Wildlife Journal Junior |url=https://nhpbs.org/wild/hornedlark.asp |website=nhpbs.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark |url=https://abcbirds.org/bird/horned-lark |website=American Bird Conservancy |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Horned Lark Life History, All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology |url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Horned_Lark/lifehistory |website=www.allaboutbirds.org |language=en}}</ref><!-- Condor105:154,109:441. FieldMusNatHistZoolSer18:343. WilsonBull18:47 (compare to current Ohio checklist http://www.ohiobirds.org/publications/OBRClist.pdf). -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* van den Berg, Arnoud (2005) Morphology of Atlas Horned Lark ''[[Dutch Birding]]'' 27(4):256\u20138\n* Small, Brian (2002) The Horned Lark on the Isles of Scilly ''[[Birding World]]'' 15(3): 111\u201320 (discusses a possible Nearctic race bird on the Isles of Scilly in 2001)\n* {{cite journal|author= Dickinso