{"title_page": "Hoover Dam Police", "text_new": "{{Infobox Law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = Hoover Dam Police\n| nativename      =\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      =\n| abbreviation    =\n| patch           = USA - Hoover Dam Police.png\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            = \n| logocaption     =\n| badge           = HooverDamPoliceBadge.JPG\n| badgecaption    =\n| flag            = \n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           = \n| mottotranslated =\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = 1931\n| formedmonthday  =\n| preceding1      =\n| dissolved       = 2017\n| superseding     =\n| employees       =\n| volunteers      =\n| budget          =\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = United States\n| countryabbr     =\n| federal         = Yes\n| map             =\n| mapcaption      =\n| sizearea        = {{convert|22|sqmi|km2|abbr=on}}\n| sizepopulation  =\n| legaljuris      = \n| governingbody   =\n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   = \n| police          = Yes\n| speciality      =\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = [[Boulder City, Nevada]]\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| sworntype       =\n| sworn           = \n| unsworntype     =\n| unsworn         =\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Vacant\n| chief1position  = Chief of Police\n| parentagency    = [[United States Bureau of Reclamation]]\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     =\n| stations        = \n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =\n| vehicles1       =\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = {{URL|usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/police.html}}\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\nThe '''Hoover Dam Police''', officially the [[Bureau of Reclamation]] Police, was a federal [[security police]] force, stationed at [[Hoover Dam]] {{convert|23|mi|km|sigfig=2}} southeast of [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. Reclamation Police Officers were stationed only at Hoover Dam.<ref>{{cite web|title=DOI Law Enforcement Jobs - Police Officer (Series 0083)|url=http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/fields/borpoliceofficer.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115063300/http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/fields/borpoliceofficer.html|archivedate=2012-01-15}}</ref> Hoover Dam was both listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1981, and was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1985.<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web\n |author=Staff \n |url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1836&ResourceType=Structure \n |title=Hoover Dam \n |accessdate=September 27, 2007 \n |work=National Historic Landmarks Program \n |publisher=National Park Service \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716043900/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1836&ResourceType=Structure \n |archivedate=July 16, 2010 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"nrhpinv\">{{Cite document |url={{NHLS url|id=81000382}} |title= National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Hoover Dam (aka Boulder Dam until 1947)] |first1= Joan |last1= Middleton |first2= Laura |last2= Feller |date= May 31, 1985 |publisher= National Park Service |format=PDF }} (Includes informative drawing of how the dam works) and {{NHLS url|id=81000382|title=Accompanying photos, from 1967 and 1997|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(1.57&nbsp;MB)}}</ref> Hoover Dam has been designated as [[Critical Infrastructure Protection|National Critical Infrastructure]]. The primary responsibilities of the Hoover Dam Police Officer were to protect the dam, the world's 57th-largest [[hydroelectric]] generating station, which provides about 2,080 [[megawatts]],<ref>{{cite web |author= Staff |url= http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/faqs/powerfaq.html |title= Frequently Asked Questions |publisher= [[Bureau of Reclamation]] |accessdate= September 23, 2008 |date= January 30, 2006 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100323052336/http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/faqs/powerfaq.html |archive-date= March 23, 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> its associated structures, and to safeguard the lives of visitors and employees. The Hoover Dam Police were assisted by unarmed Bureau of Reclamation [[Security Guard]]s who control access to reclamation facilities and deter individuals who might consider criminal activities or terrorist acts.\n\n== Closure ==\nOn October 1, 2017 the Hoover Dam Police Department was closed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bouldercityreview.com/news/dam-police-department-dissolved-park-rangers-now-patrol-facility/|title=Dam police department dissolved; park rangers now patrol facility|date=2017-12-13|website=Boulder City Review|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-14}}</ref> and the [[National Park Service]] took over law enforcement duties for the Hoover Dam.  [[National Park Service ranger|National Park Service Rangers]] from [[Lake Mead National Recreation Area]] now provide comprehensive federal law enforcement and emergency services for the facility and its visitors.  The [[United States Bureau of Reclamation|Bureau of Reclamation]] has assigned an armed Security Response Force to provide physical security for the facility.\n\n==Security concerns==\nBecause of the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks]], the [[Mike O'Callaghan \u2013 Pat Tillman Memorial Bridge|Hoover Dam Bypass]] project was expedited and traffic across the dam was restricted.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1= Illia |first1= Tony |last2= Cho |first2= Aileen |date= December 7, 2009 |title= Buffeted by High Winds and Setbacks, a Bypass Is Making History Near Hoover Dam |journal= [[Engineering News-Record]] |volume= 263 |issue= 18 |page= 18 |publisher= [[The McGraw-Hill Companies]] |location= New York |issn= 0891-9526 |url= http://enr.ecnext.com/coms2/article_intr091202HooverDam-1 |quote= (The crossing) is scheduled to open in November 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091206044406/http://enr.ecnext.com/coms2/article_intr091202HooverDam-1 |archivedate= December 6, 2009 }} \"After Sept. 11, 2001, more than 2,000 trucks a day have been diverted away from the dam.\"</ref> Some types of vehicles were inspected prior to crossing the dam while [[semi-trailer truck]]s, [[bus]]es carrying luggage, and enclosed-[[box trucks]] over {{convert|40|ft|m}} long were not allowed on the dam at all.<ref>{{cite web |author= Staff |publisher= Bureau of Reclamation |url= http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/crossingguide.pdf |format= PDF |title= Crossing Hoover Dam: A Guide for Motorists |accessdate= January 1, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100528060416/http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/crossingguide.pdf |archive-date= May 28, 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> That traffic was diverted south to a [[Colorado River]] bridge at [[Laughlin, Nevada]]. Once the bypass opened on October 19, 2010, all through traffic was rerouted on it; the roadway on the dam is now open only to employees and damn visitors.<ref name=\"Bypass open\">{{cite news |url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/oct/20/hoover-dam-bypass-bridge-opens-traffic/ |title= Hoover dam bypass bridge opens to traffic |last1= Coleman |first1= Rich |last2=Hansen |first2= Kyle  |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=October 20, 2010 |accessdate= November 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Hoover-Mead Security Zone==\nThe Hoover-Mead Security Zone encompasses {{convert|22|sqmi|km2|sigfig=2}} around Hoover Dam and [[Lake Mead]]; before the opening of the bypass, this included {{convert|3.3|mi|km|0}} of [[U.S. Highway 93]] (US&nbsp;93).<ref>{{cite web |author= Lower Colorado Region |url= http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/police/aboutus.html |title= Hoover Dam Police Department: About Us |publisher= Bureau of Reclamation |date=February 2011 |accessdate= March 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title= Federal Jobs in Law Enforcement |year= 2001 |first1= John |last1= Winton Warner |first2= Beverly |last2= Sweatman |edition= 2nd |location= Lawrenceville, NJ |publisher= Peterson's |isbn= 978-0-7689-0614-1 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/federaljobsinlaw0000warn }}</ref> Vehicles had to pass through inspection checkpoints, located on US&nbsp;93 {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} north of the dam in [[Nevada]], and {{convert|9|mi|km|spell=in}} south of the dam in [[Arizona]], before crossing.\n\nWith the opening of the bypass, traffic patterns changed dramatically. Through traffic no longer goes through a checkpoint on either side of the river. On the Nevada side, the dam road now branches off US&nbsp;93 before the checkpoint, which remains in operation to screen dam visitors. On the Arizona side, the road across the dam dead-ends in parking lots, no longer connecting to US&nbsp;93. This made the Arizona checkpoint unnecessary.<ref name=\"Bypass open\"/>\n\nThe Nevada checkpoint is manned by armed Bureau of Reclamation [[Security Guard]]s plus contracted private security personnel, as was the Arizona checkpoint before its closing. Personnel at the checkpoint may inspect any vehicle at any time before it is allowed to pass through and cross the dam.\n\n==Organization==\nHeadquartered in [[Boulder City, Nevada]].\n\n==Popular culture==\n* In the 1997 film ''[[Fools Rush In (1997 film)|Fools Rush In]]'', the character Isabel Fuentes Whitman (played by [[Salma Hayek]]) delivers a baby on the Hoover Dam assisted by the Hoover Dam Police.\n* In the 2007 film ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'', the Hoover Dam Police were shown providing external security to Sector 7.\n* In the 2015 film [[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]], the Hoover Dam is destroyed by an earthquake and the Hoover Dam police are seen escorting civilians to safety.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Law enforcement in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/police.html Official site]\n* [http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/fields/borpoliceofficer.html DOI Law enforcement site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090507000808/http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/index.html DOI jobs]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100528060416/http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/crossingguide.pdf Tips for Crossing the Dam]\n\n{{Federal law enforcement agencies of the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Clark County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Federal law enforcement agencies of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Bureau of Reclamation]]\n[[Category:Agency-specific police departments of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = Hoover Dam Police\n| nativename      =\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      =\n| abbreviation    =\n| patch           = USA - Hoover Dam Police.png\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            = \n| logocaption     =\n| badge           = HooverDamPoliceBadge.JPG\n| badgecaption    =\n| flag            = \n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           = \n| mottotranslated =\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = 1931\n| formedmonthday  =\n| preceding1      =\n| dissolved       = 2017\n| superseding     =\n| employees       =\n| volunteers      =\n| budget          =\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = United States\n| countryabbr     =\n| federal         = Yes\n| map             =\n| mapcaption      =\n| sizearea        = {{convert|22|sqmi|km2|abbr=on}}\n| sizepopulation  =\n| legaljuris      = \n| governingbody   =\n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   = \n| police          = Yes\n| speciality      =\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = [[Boulder City, Nevada]]\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| sworntype       =\n| sworn           = \n| unsworntype     =\n| unsworn         =\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Vacant\n| chief1position  = Chief of Police\n| parentagency    = [[United States Bureau of Reclamation]]\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     =\n| stations        = \n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =\n| vehicles1       =\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = {{URL|usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/police.html}}\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\nThe '''Hoover Dam Police''', officially the [[Bureau of Reclamation]] Police, was a federal [[security police]] force, stationed at [[Hoover Dam]] {{convert|23|mi|km|sigfig=2}} southeast of [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. Reclamation Police Officers were stationed only at Hoover Dam.<ref>{{cite web|title=DOI Law Enforcement Jobs - Police Officer (Series 0083)|url=http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/fields/borpoliceofficer.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115063300/http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/fields/borpoliceofficer.html|archivedate=2012-01-15}}</ref> Hoover Dam was both listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1981, and was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1985.<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web\n |author=Staff \n |url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1836&ResourceType=Structure \n |title=Hoover Dam \n |accessdate=September 27, 2007 \n |work=National Historic Landmarks Program \n |publisher=National Park Service \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716043900/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1836&ResourceType=Structure \n |archivedate=July 16, 2010 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"nrhpinv\">{{Cite document |url={{NHLS url|id=81000382}} |title= National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Hoover Dam (aka Boulder Dam until 1947)] |first1= Joan |last1= Middleton |first2= Laura |last2= Feller |date= May 31, 1985 |publisher= National Park Service |format=PDF }} (Includes informative drawing of how the dam works) and {{NHLS url|id=81000382|title=Accompanying photos, from 1967 and 1997|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(1.57&nbsp;MB)}}</ref> Hoover Dam has been designated as [[Critical Infrastructure Protection|National Critical Infrastructure]]. The primary responsibilities of the Hoover Dam Police Officer were to protect the dam, the world's 57th-largest [[hydroelectric]] generating station, which provides about 2,080 [[megawatts]],<ref>{{cite web |author= Staff |url= http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/faqs/powerfaq.html |title= Frequently Asked Questions |publisher= [[Bureau of Reclamation]] |accessdate= September 23, 2008 |date= January 30, 2006 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100323052336/http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/faqs/powerfaq.html |archive-date= March 23, 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> its associated structures, and to safeguard the lives of visitors and employees. The Hoover Dam Police were assisted by unarmed Bureau of Reclamation [[Security Guard]]s who control access to reclamation facilities and deter individuals who might consider criminal activities or terrorist acts.\n\n== Closure ==\nOn October 1, 2017 the Hoover Dam Police Department was closed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bouldercityreview.com/news/dam-police-department-dissolved-park-rangers-now-patrol-facility/|title=Dam police department dissolved; park rangers now patrol facility|date=2017-12-13|website=Boulder City Review|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-14}}</ref> and the [[National Park Service]] took over law enforcement duties for the Hoover Dam.  [[National Park Service ranger|National Park Service Rangers]] from [[Lake Mead National Recreation Area]] now provide comprehensive federal law enforcement and emergency services for the facility and its visitors.  The [[United States Bureau of Reclamation|Bureau of Reclamation]] has assigned an armed Security Response Force to provide physical security for the facility.\n\n==Security concerns==\nBecause of the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks]], the [[Mike O'Callaghan \u2013 Pat Tillman Memorial Bridge|Hoover Dam Bypass]] project was expedited and traffic across the dam was restricted.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1= Illia |first1= Tony |last2= Cho |first2= Aileen |date= December 7, 2009 |title= Buffeted by High Winds and Setbacks, a Bypass Is Making History Near Hoover Dam |journal= [[Engineering News-Record]] |volume= 263 |issue= 18 |page= 18 |publisher= [[The McGraw-Hill Companies]] |location= New York |issn= 0891-9526 |url= http://enr.ecnext.com/coms2/article_intr091202HooverDam-1 |quote= (The crossing) is scheduled to open in November 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091206044406/http://enr.ecnext.com/coms2/article_intr091202HooverDam-1 |archivedate= December 6, 2009 }} \"After Sept. 11, 2001, more than 2,000 trucks a day have been diverted away from the dam.\"</ref> Some types of vehicles were inspected prior to crossing the dam while [[semi-trailer truck]]s, [[bus]]es carrying luggage, and enclosed-[[box trucks]] over {{convert|40|ft|m}} long were not allowed on the dam at all.<ref>{{cite web |author= Staff |publisher= Bureau of Reclamation |url= http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/crossingguide.pdf |format= PDF |title= Crossing Hoover Dam: A Guide for Motorists |accessdate= January 1, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100528060416/http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/crossingguide.pdf |archive-date= May 28, 2010 |url-status= dead }}</ref> That traffic was diverted south to a [[Colorado River]] bridge at [[Laughlin, Nevada]]. Once the bypass opened on October 19, 2010, all through traffic was rerouted on it; the roadway on the dam is now open only to employees and dam visitors.<ref name=\"Bypass open\">{{cite news |url= http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/oct/20/hoover-dam-bypass-bridge-opens-traffic/ |title= Hoover dam bypass bridge opens to traffic |last1= Coleman |first1= Rich |last2=Hansen |first2= Kyle  |work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=October 20, 2010 |accessdate= November 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Hoover-Mead Security Zone==\nThe Hoover-Mead Security Zone encompasses {{convert|22|sqmi|km2|sigfig=2}} around Hoover Dam and [[Lake Mead]]; before the opening of the bypass, this included {{convert|3.3|mi|km|0}} of [[U.S. Highway 93]] (US&nbsp;93).<ref>{{cite web |author= Lower Colorado Region |url= http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/police/aboutus.html |title= Hoover Dam Police Department: About Us |publisher= Bureau of Reclamation |date=February 2011 |accessdate= March 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title= Federal Jobs in Law Enforcement |year= 2001 |first1= John |last1= Winton Warner |first2= Beverly |last2= Sweatman |edition= 2nd |location= Lawrenceville, NJ |publisher= Peterson's |isbn= 978-0-7689-0614-1 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/federaljobsinlaw0000warn }}</ref> Vehicles had to pass through inspection checkpoints, located on US&nbsp;93 {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} north of the dam in [[Nevada]], and {{convert|9|mi|km|spell=in}} south of the dam in [[Arizona]], before crossing.\n\nWith the opening of the bypass, traffic patterns changed dramatically. Through traffic no longer goes through a checkpoint on either side of the river. On the Nevada side, the dam road now branches off US&nbsp;93 before the checkpoint, which remains in operation to screen dam visitors. On the Arizona side, the road across the dam dead-ends in parking lots, no longer connecting to US&nbsp;93. This made the Arizona checkpoint unnecessary.<ref name=\"Bypass open\"/>\n\nThe Nevada checkpoint is manned by armed Bureau of Reclamation [[Security Guard]]s plus contracted private security personnel, as was the Arizona checkpoint before its closing. Personnel at the checkpoint may inspect any vehicle at any time before it is allowed to pass through and cross the dam.\n\n==Organization==\nHeadquartered in [[Boulder City, Nevada]].\n\n==Popular culture==\n* In the 1997 film ''[[Fools Rush In (1997 film)|Fools Rush In]]'', the character Isabel Fuentes Whitman (played by [[Salma Hayek]]) delivers a baby on the Hoover Dam assisted by the Hoover Dam Police.\n* In the 2007 film ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'', the Hoover Dam Police were shown providing external security to Sector 7.\n* In the 2015 film [[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]], the Hoover Dam is destroyed by an earthquake and the Hoover Dam police are seen escorting civilians to safety.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Law enforcement in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/police.html Official site]\n* [http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/fields/borpoliceofficer.html DOI Law enforcement site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090507000808/http://olesem.doi.gov/jobs/index.html DOI jobs]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100528060416/http://www.usbr.gov/lc/hooverdam/crossingguide.pdf Tips for Crossing the Dam]\n\n{{Federal law enforcement agencies of the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Clark County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Federal law enforcement agencies of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Bureau of Reclamation]]\n[[Category:Agency-specific police departments of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1000:b118:b40f:950c:baca:517f:8ad8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSecurity concer